FALCON PACK INFORMATION:
We are gearing up to continue our Falcon Pack Program again this school year with our first packs scheduled to go out Friday, October 2nd. This program is a volunteer program right from the hearts of the Clinton-Massie community. Our goal is to provide students with six meals every weekend throughout the school year. When students are fed with the proper nutrition it will help them meet developmental milestones, be more attentive, and retain learned information. To sign-up your student for our weekend Falcon Pack program please complete the following form --
https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLScyRyqjIU1dy2Z-YK7gukb3rWiQHWEwS5x1VmssZ0pIWBGPwA/viewform

This program is made possible by 100% donations from our PTO and community members. Please click https://docs.google.com/document/d/1RdOZXxmAgMNE5DpR5cWykSUie_qnb0rmIcUc-1rXy80/edit to see the list of essential food items we need to be donated to continue to make this program possible.

post_text:
Regarding High School 2020 Yearbooks:

As of right now, we do not have an anticipated arrival date for our 2019-2020 yearbooks. Our yearbook provider's printing facilities are currently operating at a 30% staff capacity. They were also shut down for an extended period of time in early spring and summer. We understand the frustration that has and may cause. We will continue to communicate with Lifetouch and get anticipated shipping dates as soon as possible. If you have any questions, please direct them to Jessica Yankel at jessica.yankel@cmfalcons.org. Thank you.

post_text: A beautiful morning in Clinton County, OH. As this lake has stood the test of time it has watched our citizens persevere. We shall persevere through this natural disaster and stand the test of time. We can only accomplish this together. #othersfirst

Clinton-Massie Local Schools has updated the Virtual Education Option information in our Fall Reopening plans. The additional information has been added to the "Option 2" section of each plan. There is also a form on our website to fill out if a family is interested in the Virtual Education Option. Please see cmfalcons.org for more details.

Hello Falcon Family Members! I hope this message finds you in good health and good spirits. A new calendar has been approved by the BOE. Our new student start date will be August 26th. The reason for the later start date is so teachers and staff can receive professional development on tools, technology, and processes that will help them deliver education and support more effectively. This training will be useful no matter what environment we find ourselves in this school year. If you have any questions feel free to call 937-289-2471 or email matt.baker@cmfalcons.org.

We also hope to receive recommendations on how to reopen schools in the fall from the Governor's Office today. We will use these recommendations to finish our plans for in-person attendance and our virtual education option. Thank you for your patience. Stay Safe!

post_text: Clinton-Massie Local Schools is proud to announce that we are the recipient of a $10,000 grant from HealthFirst of Clinton County. The money will be used to further expand the Community Handicapped Accessible Outdoor Fitness Center located behind the annex (near the entrance to the YMCA Daycare). As stated by our award letter this project "exemplifies the mission of HealthFirst for Clinton County". There are numerous items already in place but this grant will bring the project to near completion. We are thankful to HealthFirst of CC and Cindy Stenger, Wellness Coordinator and District School Nurse. Cindy's tireless efforts have brought this dream to life!

post_text: Wilmington City Schools hosted a meeting today with multiple stakeholders in the field of education and public health to discuss the opening of schools in the fall of 2020. The superintendents of all four county public schools were present along with Dr. Terry Holten, Medical Director of the Clinton County Health District and Pam Walker-Bauer, Clinton County Health Commissioner. The discussions focused on potential plans that may be implemented for the next school year. All parties agreed to work together and hope to provide plans to their respective communities in the near future. The county superintendents pledged to meet multiple times in the next month to help share ideas around safety. Dr, Holten and Mrs. Bauer also pledge their support and attendance if called upon.

post_text: Did you know the Falcon Pantry also distributes clothes to those in need? It's true. We have hundreds of items to sort through to prepare for a giveaway. We need as many people that are willing to help to join us on Monday, June 15th for a workday starting at 9:00 am. We will have gloves, hand sanitizer, and masks available. Helpers can go to the back of the annex and head toward the doors with the large red Falcon Pantry collection bin next to it. The main purpose of the work day is to sort clothing. We will handout items from 4-6 pm on June 16th. All clothing will be given away for free. Summer clothing items will be available. #fuelthepositive

post_text: Hello to all of our Falcon Family Members! Thank you again for being so flexible during these times of uncertainty. We know that our families have numerous questions about how the next school year will be conducted. We understand the anxiety this lack of knowledge causes to a family and especially our students. Our goal is to make sound decisions that are student-centered and fiscally responsible at the same time. We are meeting as an administration team regularly to discuss our options and look for savings because of the state funding reductions. As we move forward we will update families as soon as possible. As plans surface from the state and other school districts we understand this may prompt our residents to want the same answers at the same time. We ask for grace and patience as we take our time and make decisions that hopefully will not have too many revisions once posted. Thank you again and enjoy your summer!

Good afternoon all. I wanted to share a small change to the locker-cubby pick-up this evening. We were being very cautious when we split up the alphabet into three parts to ensure the lines would not be too long. Last night things went very smoothly and we are opening pick-up time from 4-7 this evening to all grades and all letters of the alphabet. No matter if you are A-G, H-N or O to Z please feel free to stop by tonight! We will also have an all student pick-up time tomorrow from 12-2 pm. This will eliminate the need for the rescheduled evening pick-up on Thursday. The same traffic patterns apply for both pick-ups.

If you can't make either day don't fret! We will have days in the summer to pick-up locker/cubby contents which will include also gym locker contents. Thanks for your understanding and flexibility! It was so fun to see a few students last night!! Stay Safe! #fuelthepositive

Again, tonight, all grades and last names from 4-7 pm.
Tomorrow from 12-2 pm all ages and last names!
No Thursday evening time will be needed.
Summer dates TBD!

post_text:
We have received final numbers from ODE, and we will be losing $344,000 the remainder of this school year. That is equivalent to 1 bi-monthly payment that we receive in state funding. However, we are getting $153,000 in CARES funding. We are still waiting to hear what next year will bring, and are prepared to tighten things up. I will present a five year forecast at the Board meeting tonight that is very reminiscent of a pre-levy forecast. We will be streaming the audio at www.youtube.com/channel/UCfT6rkUun7Eh2t0rPxUeFJA/live and you can call in to 937-303-8069 during the public participation portion. I will not be out for dinner beforehand - hopefully we can resume those soon!
#MassieMoneyMonday

post_text: Do you want to say "THANK YOU" to your teachers? Here is how you can help spread the word on how much Clinton-Massie Teachers care about their students. We have created a Flipgrid that we want to share with all of our teachers in honor of Teacher Appreciation Week. If you have a moment, please go to Flipgrid.com, enter the flip code ( at the top left of the page) 1203ea69, and record up to 30 seconds thanking our teachers! They find ways to give us their support, time, and encouragement and we want to make sure they know how much we all appreciate what they do! You can also post your own video of appreciation on Instagram or Twitter using the #fuelthepositive or tag cmfalcons_news. If video is not your thing, please consider sending a teacher a quick email or note. Thank you for helping us celebrate our teachers! Stay safe!!

A big thank you to those who were able to get your employers to deduct your income tax - we received our first payment for January through March and it was about $5000 more than we had forecasted!
We're still keeping a close eye on the effect of the COVID closures, especially at the state level. Other local treasurers are thinking there may be a 5% reduction in state funding for next year which would equate to about $400,000 for us. Here's a more recent article that was posted about the possibilities: https://www.cleveland.com/open/2020/04/education-funding-cuts-seen-as-likely-as-gov-mike-dewine-considers-how-to-balance-state-budget.html
#MassieMoneyMonday

Remember to continue to check our website at cmfalcons.org for regularly updated information. Our district SMORE (e-newsletter) is updated with new and helpful information.

https://www.smore.com/guahf

We do continue to ask for grace and patience during these unprecedented times. There is no playbook for this situation. We are doing the best we can and making the best decisions based on the information we have at the time. It is never our intent to harm students or their experience but we do have to recognize we are in a new normal. This is very emotional time for all students and parents, especially Seniors. Although we cannot replicate a traditional end of year experience for all students, athletes, and parents, we are trying our best to recognize the efforts of each group. Thank you for your understanding in this very difficult time.

post_text:
Hello Falcon Family Members,

We wanted to first say thank you for grace and patience in these unprecedented times. We recognize the tremendous effort put out by our students and staff to continue learning while we navigate through the rest of the school year. Although academics are important, the most important thing to us is the health and well-being of our staff and students. With that thought in mind please watch the video below. We are calling the next few days the Family Focus Four. We want this four day weekend to be all about the family! We are asking students and staff to disconnect from the world of academics and just focus on their families in order to renew their energy. It is our heartfelt desire to lower the anxiety this situation has caused by implementing this Family Focus Four directive. Thank you for your support! #fuelthepositive

This post is for Warren County Residents only. We were asked to pass this information along.

Warren County JFS COVID-19 TANF/PRC Response Program.

What benefits do I receive through this program? If approved, your household will receive a one-time check of $250.00 to assist you with any expenses, you have during this time of great need. The check will be mailed to the address provided on your application and will be made out to the person listed as the primary person on the application.

See the following shared documents for more details.

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1eeO5OyfCDyIzDXSTwsq8CvtJfitRjBG3/view?usp=sharing

https://drive.google.com/file/d/17tCJHdXlVVBOOOpOwZkZrWwPQJHJQICt/view?usp=sharing

Questions? Call Warren County Department of Human Services at (513)695-1420.

GREAT NEWS!!! Amid the uncertainty right now, we have received some good news from the Ohio Department of Education. Through their School Bus Purchase Program, we will be receiving $35,400 towards the purchase of a new bus (~$90,000)! This will allow us to take our oldest route bus out of service. If there is money leftover from other schools, we may get even more! #MassieMoneyMonday
Also, this is a reminder that our Board meeting for this evening has been CANCELED. We are looking into rescheduling a virtual meeting.

post_text:
More Donations Needed!!!

We will be attempting to do another food distribution next week (Monday or Tuesday depending on the amount of donations received this weekend). We have handed out hundreds of bags and boxes to needy families. We cannot say thank you enough times to all the people that have volunteered and donated. We are calling for another round of donations. We have attached a list below of items that are needed to help sustain the current level of assistance. We know that finding some of these items is hard right now. Anything that you can donate would help. Distribution will be contingent on the governor's directives over the weekend! If you would like to drop off donations feel free to stop by on Friday through Sunday and place them in the carts outside the MS entrance. We will move them inside throughout the weekend. Thank you again for what are community is doing for our students while we are finding our new normal! #fuelthepositive #thistooshallpass #sicknessendskindnessisforever

The middle school band and choir performed an excellent show to a full crowd tonight!

post_text: Clinton-Massie Local Schools would like to announce that we have joined a system called G.E.T.S. (Government Emergency Telecommunications Service). This system works through our landline phones. When dialing a special number given to us by the Department of Homeland Security our calls will by-pass all other calls to go to "the front of the line" even if regular phone lines are clogged. This will benefit us in the case of a major emergency and too many people are trying to call in to or out of the district phone lines. There is no cost to set-up or use this system. Thank you to Dann Sternsher and the Safety Committee for bringing this to our attention. By employing this system we hope to aid in the quick response of emergency personnel in the case of a major incident or natural disaster. #fuelthepositive

post_text:
Safe Sitter® Classes
YMCA Safe Sitter is a nationally-recognized program that gives kids ages 11-15 the skills and knowledge needed to safely care for children infants through school age. In this 1-day workshop, participants will learn choking rescue skills, how to handle life-threatening emergencies, how to keep themselves safe, when and how to call for help, and child development knowledge to help them become a safer and better sitter. Registration fee includes the Safe Sitter workbook. Participants need to bring a packed lunch and a drink.

May 2nd, 2020, this class will be offered at Clinton-Massie Local Schools. Please register at the following address. https://countrysideymca.org/activities-and-more/programs-classes/education/health-and-safety-classes/safe-sitter-workshop.html

post_text:
Each month Jacque Proctor's class celebrates their hard work in Writers Workshop with a Writers Celebration. In January, they invited families into the classroom to help celebrate. Each student got to put their story under the document camera and use a microphone to read it to everyone.

Mrs. Proctor also shared the following about her students celebrating the 100th Day of school:
"To help our class think beyond our classroom and into the community, I shared the needs of a local animal shelter with them. Students were encouraged to do jobs/chores at home to earn quarters. We set a goal to collect 100 quarters to donate to the Wilmington Area Humane Society by our 100th Day of School. We surpassed our goal by collecting 252 quarters ($63). A volunteer from the Humane Society came in and spoke with the class about the needs of local cats and dogs and to accept our donation."
PC/CC: Jacque Proctor

I'll be at the 73 Grill from 5:30-6:30 prior to the meeting if you'd like to hear more! #MassieMoneyMonday

post_text: For the past 8 days our 8th grade students have been working on a Christmas Carol PBL. Students were asked to design a museum exhibit that reflected a theme from Charles Dickinson's classic. Students had to create and design a three-dimensional door knocker, which was a key component in the story. Students also had to share their timeline of the Victorian Era. Drawings of period specific items were also included in their displays. The 8th grade teachers were very excited about the high engagement levels of their students. #fuelthepositive

post_text: Just a friendly reminder that Tuesday, November 5th, 2019, will be a two hour late arrival day for all Clinton-Massie Local Schools (just like if we had to call for a snow delay). We are working with the Clinton County Board of Elections to make the new polling location here at CMLS as accessible as possible. We will collect information to further assess the need to delay school on election days moving forward. If you have any questions or concerns please contact Matt Baker, CMLS Superintendent directly at matt.baker@cmfalcons.org or call 289-2471. Thanks!

post_text:
Preschool Family Fun!

Friday, October 25th was Family Fun day for our preschool team! We had parents and students that came for time together to play, sensory "make and take" station, games, snacks, and a special section about "Dina School". We also incorporated a parent education piece about social/emotional skills for preschoolers from our Early Childhood Mental Health Consultant, Tiesha Widmer. We had a great turn out and look forward to our next family day.

@ Clinton Massie Local Schools

post_text: School finance update! During an Ohio Association of School Board Officials meeting last week, I found out that ALL districts are "on the guarantee" like we are for FY20 & FY21. This means the state isn't using a formula anymore, they are just keeping the money the same as FY19. The adjustment comes in the Student Wellness & Success funds, in which we are receiving $144,056 this year. Also, the Cupp-Patterson Fair School Funding model (new formula) is still in play, but most likely as part of the next biennial budget. #MassieMoneyMonday I will be at J&Ds from 5:30 - 6:30 if you want to discuss!

The Clinton-Massie Local School District is preparing for the future. Our district is starting the process of creating a strategic plan and we need your input. Please provide your feedback through the Thought Exchange system. This system allows you to anonymously enter feedback and react to what others are saying all within the privacy of your home. We look forward to using the information we gather to better our school district. Thank you for your participation!

https://my.thoughtexchange.com/#768846383/hub

Please share this with those in the community that may not have a student in the district. It is hard to get input from community members that are not directly connected to the school. We want to hear from all stakeholders!

post_text: As many of you have heard by now we have lost a member of the Falcon Family. Brian Mudd passed away last night in the presence of family and friends at his home in Wilmington. He will be missed by all! He continues to be an inspiration for us to battle adversity with a drive and determination that will lift the spirits of those around us. Please keep his family and friends in your prayers as they work through this very difficult time. We will be sharing information about his "Celebration of Life" ceremony soon. We expect it to be sometime Saturday afternoon and it will be held in the HS gymnasium. Thank you to all those that have already reached out with messages of support! Hug your loved ones just a little bit tighter today because every day we have together is special!

post_text: We would like to take a moment and update our community on the recent lockdown. Today the elementary school was put into lockdown for the purpose of investigating a potential threat. After an investigation by the adminstration and CC Sheriff's Department the threat was found to have no merit. The HS/MS was also put into a lockdown as a precaution. We are working through the details and speaking with students. Thank you for your understanding on this matter.
